<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-058-576  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 058 576.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC World  March 1989 v7 n3 p43(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>To sue, perchance to win. (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Bunnell, David.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Law suits by software giants like Lotus Development Corp andAshton-Tate serve to diminish competition more than protectintellectual property.andP;  Lotus has filed a suit against PaperbackSoftware claiming the company's low-cost spreadsheet packageviolated the 'look and feel' of 1-2-3, Lotus' popular spreadsheet.andO;Since the suit was filed in 1986, Paperback Software has sufferedfrom the legal cost of the challenge.andP;  A similar lawsuit has beenfiled by Ashton-Tate against Fox Software claiming their Foxbaseproduct has violated dBase territory.andP;  These companies shouldrecognize that the imitation products are simply a means ofenhancing the market position and development efforts of theestablished products.andP;  Competition is valuable for the market,while the intimidation of legal action diminishes the effort ofinnovative companies.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Ashton-Tate (cases)Fox Software Inc. (cases).andO;Topic:     Law SuitCompatible SoftwareIntellectual PropertyUser InterfaceCost Benefit AnalysisProduct Development.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>